WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:06.000
Hello, everybody. My name is Ryan Johnson, and I'm a data science advisor here at Posit.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And welcome to this month's Enterprise Community Meetup, where we'll discuss an end-to-end data science workflow using Posit Team.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:24.000
As a reminder, this will be a recurring event on the last Wednesday of every month, and we hope it'll serve as a good primer for those new to Posit Team,

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
but also helps current Posit Team users become more familiar with our tools.

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Every month, we will cover a different topic and highlight all three tools within Posit Team.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
We have Posit Workbench, Posit Connect, and Posit Package Manager.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:52.000
During and after each presentation, there will be a few members of the Posit Team in the chat to address any questions you have about our tools, workflows, licensing, and anything else you may be curious about.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:01.000
So this month, we have a pretty exciting topic for everyone, especially those within the life sciences, healthcare, and pharmaceutical space.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:14.000
So we are going to use Posit Team to create a Shiny application of clinical trial data in R, all while discussing best practices for working within what's known as a validated environment.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:26.000
As we go through today's session, I'll be sure to stop and note various ways Posit Team can help support a validated compute environment and encourage good coding practices.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:28.000
So let's get started.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I first want to make sure everyone on the call has a solid, high-level understanding of Posit Team.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:39.000
So starting up here at the very top, we have our data scientists and analysts.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
These are the folks writing code and creating insights using Posit Workbench.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And they can use whatever language they want, including R and Python, as well as any development environment they choose, including the RStudio IDE, JupyterLab, Jupyter Notebooks, and VS Code.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:10.000
Now for the R developers, they may be creating insights like Shiny applications, pins, R Markdown documents, or APIs using the Plumber package.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And for Python developers, they have a home to create interactive applications using things like Streamlit, Dash, Bokeh, Shiny.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:28.000
They can also create documents using Jupyter Notebooks or even Quarto, and APIs using Flask and FastAPI.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Now once the developers create content, they need a way to share it with the people that need to see it, including decision makers, coworkers, clients, or maybe even just friends and family.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:47.000
And so that's the role of Posit Connect, which is our professional publishing platform.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And finally, we have Posit Package Manager, which helps organize and centralize the great open source R and Python packages your team uses, as well as host and distribute any internally developed R and Python packages you've created.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:15.000
So for today's session, we are going to start within Posit Workbench, and we will leverage the RStudio IDE to create a Shiny application in R using clinical trial data.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And then we'll publish this application to Posit Connect, all within the context of a validated environment.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Now just for awareness, the clinical trial data that we'll use today is publicly available.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:33.000
It's been properly de-identified and cleansed for demonstration purposes.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:41.000
So before we actually dive into this workflow, let's take a few moments just to talk more about this clinical trial data set.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Now what is it? Where does it come from?

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:54.000
Now as a high level overview, clinical trials, they are conducted usually to assess the efficacy of some disease intervention.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:08.000
So during the trial, data will be collected, organized, and eventually that data will find itself inside of an analysis ready data set called an atom or analysis data model data set.

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:18.000
So these atom data sets are usually what's submitted to various regulatory agencies, such as the Food and Drug Administration or FDA.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.000
So here's actually a quick glimpse into what this example atom data set looks like.

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Now we are only going to focus on the columns that you see here, which include things like subject ID number, the treatment group, age, BMI, height, weight, and years of education.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:42.000
So these subject level variables are usually found in the data set.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:52.000
Now while this data is not particularly large, it does contain numerous descriptive columns, and it can be a challenge to create static insights such as plots and tables to explore them all.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:59.000
So for this reason, we will create an interactive web application using this data set.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:07.000
It does contain numerous descriptive columns, and it can be a challenge to create static insights such as plots and tables to explore them all.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:15.000
So for this reason, we will create an interactive web application using this data set.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:28.000
So this application will allow viewers to explore the data for themselves and compare various subject level variables between the three treatments groups, which we'll talk about a little bit more in a bit.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:36.000
So to start, let's open an RStudio session within Posit Workbench.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:45.000
So here we have in Posit Workbench on the right hand side, you can see some of the projects I've been working on, but we'll go ahead and click New Session.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And you can see right off the bat that I have a choice between Jupyter Notebooks, JupyterLab, RStudio Pro, and VS Code.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
So for today, we're going to select RStudio.

00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:04.000
And now before I start this session, I want to briefly describe our demo computing environment here at Posit.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:13.000
So we host Posit Workbench within a clustered environment, which is managed by a tool called Kubernetes, which you can see here.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:30.000
So for validated compute environments, it's often necessary that certain aspects of this RStudio session are controlled for, including what R version is being used, which R or system packages come pre-installed.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
And so that's where tools like Docker come into play.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:41.000
And here at the very bottom, you can see that I have a choice for various Docker images I can deploy within.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
