00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
I'm the only one that can actually view

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:52.000
or edit this application.

00:18:53.000 --> 00:18:55.000
And if I want to be very specific,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
I can maybe share this with Rachel.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
And now we would be the only two

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:03.000
that can view this content.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:05.000
I have a few other options as well.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
I can select all users login required.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
And that just means that if someone has the credentials

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:13.000
to log into the Posit Connect server,

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:15.000
they can view this content.

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.000
Or I can select anyone no login required.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:21.000
And that basically means that if someone has the URL

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:23.000
at the top of my screen,

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:25.000
which you can customize down here,

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:27.000
they can then view this content.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.000
So it pretty much opens it up to the world.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
And the people that are seeing it,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
they don't have to know anything about Shiny, R, Connect.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:37.000
They can just view it like they would any other website.

00:19:38.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Okay, so to wrap things up,

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:44.000
let's actually go back to Posit Workbench.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:47.000
And we're just going to take a moment

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.000
to record our R environment,

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
so that anyone else or probably more likely

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:56.000
our future self could reproduce our work.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:19:59.000
So some of the things we'll want to record

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:02.000
include which R version did I use,

00:20:03.000 --> 00:20:04.000
which R packages we use,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.000
and what versions of those packages,

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:08.000
as well as which repositories we use

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:10.000
to install the packages.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:12.000
Now, as I mentioned earlier,

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:14.000
we're going to use an R package

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:17.000
called renv to help out here.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
So renv, it's an open source R package,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:22.000
and its name is shorthand

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:24.000
for reproducible environments.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:25.000
So we're going to use renv

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:27.000
to record our R environment

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:30.000
into what's known as an renv log file.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:32.000
As you can see right here,

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:34.000
I'll go ahead and click on this.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:40.000
So this is the current state of our log file,

00:20:41.000 --> 00:20:42.000
which was created when we first initialized

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:44.000
this RStudio project.

00:20:45.000 --> 00:20:46.000
And we can read it from top to bottom.

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:48.000
You can see we're using R for this project,

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:50.000
version 4.2.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:53.000
And here are the active repositories

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:56.000
when I first initialized this project,

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.000
which we'll obviously need to update

00:20:59.000 --> 00:21:01.000
to reflect our validator repository.

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:03.000
Now, everything below this,

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:05.000
starting on line 11 right here,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:07.000
this is information about the packages

00:21:08.000 --> 00:21:09.000
in this project,

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
including which version I need.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:13.000
Now, as you can see,

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:15.000
we are only seeing one package here,

00:21:16.000 --> 00:21:17.000
the renv package.

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:19.000
And so we'll need to update this log file

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:21.000
to reflect the current state

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:23.000
of our package environment.

00:21:24.000 --> 00:21:25.000
So I'm going to open up my console down here,

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:27.000
clear my screen.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:29.000
And I'm going to run from the renv package

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.000
the snapshot function.

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:36.000
We'll just ignore that message for right now.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:39.000
And we're going to see some text right here.

00:21:41.000 --> 00:21:42.000
So I think this is one of my,

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:44.000
the favorite parts about the renv package

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:46.000
is that it'll actually inform us

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:50.000
what will happen if we decide to proceed.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:53.000
So it's letting us know that all these packages

00:21:54.000 --> 00:21:56.000
that are not currently in our log file,

00:21:57.000 --> 00:21:58.000
as represented by this asterisk,

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:00.000
will be written to the log file

00:22:01.000 --> 00:22:02.000
with the version reflecting,

00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:05.000
reflected in my current R environment.

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:07.000
So if this all looks good to you,

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:09.000
which it looks pretty good to me,

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:11.000
do you want to proceed?

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:13.000
I'll hit Y for yes and hit enter.

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:18.000
And so now if we open up our log file,

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:20.000
you can see there's a lot more packages in here,

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:23.000
but I didn't have to edit this myself at all.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And it is now reflecting my current R environment

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.000
and all those packages inside and the correct versions.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:34.000
And so this file can be shared with other users

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.000
or as a companion file for FDA submission, for example.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:41.000
And it can be used to reproduce your R environment

00:22:42.000 --> 00:22:44.000
and your analysis results.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.000
And so with that,

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.000
we have come to the end of our workflow for today.

00:22:50.000 --> 00:22:52.000
So I hope everyone found this month's demo helpful.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:54.000
And we'd certainly love to chat more

00:22:55.000 --> 00:22:56.000
about how Posit team can assist

00:22:57.000 --> 00:22:58.000
with your data science workflows

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:01.000
and support a validated compute environment.

00:23:02.000 --> 00:23:03.000
So feel free to stick around

00:23:04.000 --> 00:23:05.000
